Abstract = {Psychopathy has been widely studied among criminal populations. Most
   analyses address it in institutionalized populations, however, the
   present study examines the psychometric properties of the Levenson
   Self-Report Psychopathy Scale (LSRP) in 642 court-referred
   partner-violent men serving suspended prison sentences. The confirmatory
   factor analysis confirmed the two-factor structure (primary and
   secondary psychopathy) of the original scale. The resulting scale was a
   brief-form version of the LSRP that presents satisfactory data in terms
   of internal consistency and criterion validity, and significant positive
   correlations with measures of intimate partner violence (IPV),
   antisocial personality traits and impulsivity. In terms of known-groups
   validity, meanwhile, psychopathy was found to decrease with the age of
   the participants. In this light, the LSRP brief-form offers adequate
   psychometric reliability as an instrument to measure primary and
   secondary psychopathy in partner -violent men serving suspended
