Abstract = {Nonprofit brand image plays an important role in shaping consumers'
   charitable donations and therefore nonprofit organizations must be aware
   of how consumers perceive them. This research examines nonprofit brand
   image and reports findings from three empirical studies, which aim to
   offer a better conceptualization and measurement of the concept. Study 1
   investigates the psychometric properties of the Michel and Rieunier's
   (2012) nonprofit brand image scales with a sample from the UK, and
   reports key methodological limitations. Specifically, discriminant and
   convergent validity tests highlight the need for further research into
   the dimensionality of the nonprofit brand image measures. Subsequently,
   studies 2 and 3 offer an improved conceptualization and measurement of
   nonprofit brand image and validate the scales via the use of 2 separate
