Year = {2019},
Volume = {9},
Number = {3},
Month = {JUL},
Abstract = {Lay definitions tend to conceptualize stress as negative, undesirable,
   and maladaptive. However, contemporary stress models emphasize the
   differentiation between negative and positive stress responses, known as
   distress and eustress. Despite prominent theoretical conceptualisations
   accepting the existence of eustress, the vast majority of stress
   measures tend to focus exclusively on the distress response. The current
   study introduces the Adolescent Distress-Eustress Scale (ADES) which
   holistically captures both aspects of the stress response, bridging the
   gap between theory and measurement and counteracting the typically
   negatively focused approach to stress research. The ADES was
   systematically developed and tested in a socio-educationally diverse
   sample of 981 adolescents (M-age = 15.19, 50.62\% female). The finalized
   self-report scale consists of two 5-item subscales, individually
   indexing distress and eustress. Initial psychometric properties of the
   ADES are promising, and the scale has the potential to meet the needs of
   researchers, schools, and organizations.},
